Here is a detailed plan to migrate Earth Observatory backend microservices currently running as Docker containers on a single EC2 instance into a managed Kubernetes environment (Amazon EKS).

Key outcomes:

•	Move container runtime to EKS with images stored in ECR.
•	Use ALB Ingress Controller for path-based routing (same host headers).
•	Keep environment variables, Dockerfile and Manifest Files in SSM Parameter Store and fetch them in jenkins while building the services.
•	Implement CI/CD via Jenkins to build the application, push images to ecr, and deploy the service to EKS cluster using the manifest files stored in the parameter store.

Scope (what's included)

Included:
•	All backend microservices currently deployed on the EC2 Docker host
•	Docker image build & push to ECR
•	Kubernetes manifests (Deployment, Service, Ingress)
•	Jenkins pipeline changes to support EKS deployment
•	ALB Ingress configuration and Route53 update for cutover
•	Smoke tests, rollback plan, and monitoring integration

What’s already set up in our EKS cluster

Cluster & Nodes

•	Running EKS 1.32  (latest stable).
•	2 nodegroups Services. 

Namespace: Created a namespace with the project name for dev env.

