Config & Secrets

In DS-dev, we have a service account secrets-manager-access-sa → for fetching secrets from AWS Secrets Manager / SSM directly inside pods.

In DS, there’s satellite-sa → might be used by one specific service.

Ingress
•	ALB ingress controller is installed and active.
•	Both Prod and Dev ingress objects point to the same ALB but route based on host header (api.astra.in).

Migration Plan:

Step 1: Create an ECR Repository for each service in eo.
Step 2: Create New Nodegroup for EO Application Services – Isolated from IS
Step 3: Create a Parameter Store for each service to store the manifest files. We can use the existing ENV and Dockerfile for building.
Step 4: Create Kubernetes Namespaces for EO Application. For example – eo-dev, eo-staging and eo-prod
Step 5: Create Service Accounts in each namespace for backend services to access other AWS resources.
Step 6: Create Deployment and Service Files for each service and store them in the parameter store
Step 7: Create a new Jenkins pipeline for each service to check out code from GitHub, fetch the env files, Dockerfile, and manifest files from parameter store, build the Docker images, push the image to ecr repo, Assume EKS IAM role, aws eks update-kubeconfig, and deploy it in eks cluster.
(Note: Keep the EC2 pipeline only as a rollback standby until full validation and decommission.)
Step 8: Configure 3 Ingresses using ALB ingress annotations for path-based routing and host api.astra.in, devapi.astra.in and stageapi.astra.in (3 envs)
Step 9: Once the ingresses are applied Go to Route 53, and change the pointer of each subdomain host header to their respective load balancers.
Step 10: Testing & Validation: Verify EKS node security groups allow outbound to RDS port 33306 and RabbitMQ 5672. End-to-end tests through ALB Ingress (curl with Host header) before DNS cutover
Rollback:
If any critical error occurs, revert the Route53 alias to the previous ALB (document current TTLs to make rollback quick). 



